cards.desc:
The implementation of emotional states in a machine is a challenging and quite explored topic since it can be considered as the cornerstone for the implementation of human-like consciousness and possibly cognition. 
In the NeuCogAr project we have proposed a neurobiologically plausible approach for the re-implementation of affects in a computational system. We adopted the neuropsychological model called “cube of emotions” created by Hugo Lövheim. This model creates the correlation between affects and monoamine neuromodulators: noradrenaline, serotonin, dopamine. 
To provide bio-realistic simulation integration with a robotic embodiment and partly remove a borderline between the simulated brain in spiking neural network (sNN) and real world, we proposed the “Robot dream” architecture with two-phase calculations. The first phase involves lightweight real time calculations, while at the second phase the bio-realistic based on sNN calculations are performed within a simulated “sleeping brain”. This way, a possible approach for the robotic system control system could be based on memristors application. With memristors being perceived as close to bio-realistic implementation of synapses, we currently see them as especially organic implementation with low energy consuming candidates for the artificial neuron basic elements. 
We have presented the high-level architecture of organic memristive based neuron hardware implementation. Current schematic contains n+m memristive elements, where n is number of excitatory synapses and m is number of inhibitory synapses; generator of action potential impulses and two complex feedback loops for inhibitor and excitatory training. In case of excitatory synapses: memristive elements are trained using Hebbian learning rule of STDP; in case of inhibitory synapses memristive elements are trained using “sombrero” STDP rule. This work is a position paper with the goal to implement bio-plausible hardware neuron architecture, based on which we hope to implement complex structures of a mammalian brain: for example the dopamine pathways of a rat brain. Further, organic memristor based system will be integrated into a biologically-inspired robotic system, which will allow for a significant technological breakthrough in robotics and will affect such fields of robotics as natural emotion generation, human-robot interaction, reinforced learning of non-deterministic decision making, and many others.

1. The rationale for how mono amines are mapped to the various computing processes needs to be much more clearly explained - at this point it is not explained in the manuscript. For example - why is dopamine related to storage volume? and why is adrenaline is related to working memory? And why are both orthogonal to each other? There is plenty of biological evidence that dopamine is key to working memory, not only its capacity but gating and performance, and that there is an important and significant interaction between dopaminergic and serotonergic circuits.

2. I am not an expert in computing systems, but it is not clear in the paper why computing utilization ( I imagine its the computational load allocated to the process at hand? or is it a general measure of computing load?) related to emotions? This link between the emotions and the computing measures tracked needs to be clarified.

4. In figure 2 - I am not sure what is plotted as activity - is it firing rate or a cell or for the whole simulated are? The numbers are not really biologically realistic if its the former - very few cells can fire over 100 Hz and even 65 Hz is too high for sustained firing for cortical pyramidal neurons. This point needs to be clarified.

In addition, in many places, it was hard to understand the text. English needs to be checked not only for grammar but also syntactically and stylistically.

In summary, the paper needs to be revised and improved before one can really drudge its impact and technical quality of the results.

cards.desc:
----------- Review -----------
The paper presents a short evaluation of a number of existing architectures with respect to their ability to represent emotions. The authors argue that the main criterion is neurobiological similarity, which is quite different from the usual perspective of cognitive modeling, which tends to argue for functional similarity. Emotions are not chemical or biological states, but functional ones. Thus, the authors would have to argue their point, which they sadly omit.

The discussion of the presented architectures is very superficial and often wrong. For instance, the authors claim that Roz Picard's work forms the foundation of all existing models. The authors do not focus on architectures that claim to model emotion in particular (and some of the most prominent ones are missing). With respect to those they discuss, they seem to have limited knowledge, not exceeding a cursory scanning of a Wikipedia article. For instance, when discussing emotion in ACT-R, the authors should have a look at the various different emotion extensions implemented for the architecture, instead of just describing ACT-R's core idea.

As a result, the literature review is of very limited value. A better review would certainly be useful, but several of those already exist.

The authors suggest that their own architecture, which is still in development, meets their unspecified criteria better, but this architecture is not the object of this paper.

The writing is clear, but the grammar is not fit for publication in conference proceedings.

The re-implementation of  real-time robotic system is one of challenging problems. We propose newel of the integration of biologically plausible simulation of mammalian brain with real-time/semi-real-time autonomous robotic system using metaphor of “wake-dream” phases of a mammalian life. During the “wake” phase a robotic system stores the inbound sensory information in form of pseudo-neuronal activities and is manged via light-weight rule-based system, in contrast during the “dream” phase “sleeping brain” plays-back the stored pseudo-neural activities over simulated spiking neural network and later using “reverse translation” translates updated neuronal structures in form of light-weight rules of the robotic system.
We call the proposed architecture “Robot dream”.
